revision.text:
{{short description|Ancient Greek mythological figure}}
'''Aetna''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: {{lang|grc|Αἴτνη}}, ''Aἴtnē'') was in [[Greek mythology|Greek]] and [[Roman mythology]] a [[Sicily|Sicilian]] [[nymph]]<ref>{{Citation  | last = Schmitz  | first = Leonhard  | contribution = Aetna  | editor-last = Smith  | editor-first = William| title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]  | volume = 1  | pages = 54  | place = Boston| year = 1870  | contribution-url = http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0063.html }}</ref> and, according to [[Alcimus]],<ref>[[Alcimus]], ''ap. Schol. Theocrit.'' i. 65; Ellis, [https://archive.org/stream/aetna___00elliuoft#page/n51/mode/2up p. l].</ref> a daughter of [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]] and [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]], or of [[Briareus]]. [[Stephanus of Byzantium]] says that according to one account Aetna was a daughter of [[Oceanus]].<ref>[[Stephanus of Byzantium]], s.v. [https://archive.org/stream/stephanibyzanti00meingoog#page/n508/mode/1up Παλιχη]; Ellis, [https://archive.org/stream/aetna___00elliuoft#page/n51/mode/2up pp. l&ndash;li].</ref> [[Simonides]] said that she had acted as arbitrator between [[Hephaestus]] and [[Demeter]] respecting the possession of Sicily.  By [[Zeus]] or Hephaestus she became the mother of the [[Palici]].<ref>[[Servius]]. ''ad Aen.'', ix. 584.</ref>  [[Mount Etna|Mount Aetna]] in Sicily was believed to have derived its name from her, and under it Zeus buried [[Typhon]], [[Enceladus (giant)|Enceladus]], or Briareus. The mountain itself was believed to be the place in which Hephaestus and the [[Cyclops]] made the thunderbolts for Zeus.<ref>[[Euripides]]. ''[[Cyclops (play)|Cyclops]]'', 296.</ref><ref>[[Sextus Propertius|Propertius]], iii. 15. 21.</ref><ref>[[Cicero]]. ''[[De Divinatione]]'', ii. 19.</ref>

