{{Merge|Interconnector|date=June 2018}} {{multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width = 200 | image1 = HVDC Europe.svg | caption1 = [[High-voltage direct current]] interconnections in western Europe in 2008 - red are existing links, green are under construction, and blue are proposed. | image2 = Power_Grid_of_Japan.svg | caption2 = Map of Japan's electricity transmission network, showing differing systems between regions. Unusually for a national grid, different regions run at completely different frequencies. }} An '''electrical interconnector''' is a high power AC or DC connection, typically across national borders<ref>[https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/electricity/transmission-networks/electricity-interconnectors ''Electricity interconnectors'' ofgem]</ref> or between different [[electrical grid]]s.<ref>[https://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/Interconnection.pdf ''LARGE-SCALE ELECTRICITY INTERCONNECTION'' 2016]</ref> They can be formed of [[submarine power cable]]s or [[underground power cable]]s or [[overhead power line]]s.
The longest interconnection at 2016 was the undersea NorNed link between Norway and the Netherlands, spanning nearly 600&nbsp;km and delivering 700 MW of high voltage direct current power.<ref>IEA/OECD (2016) Large-Scale Electricity Interconnection: Technology and prospects for cross-regional networks, (IEA, Paris)</ref>
